{
  "terms": [
    {
      "term": "ADS",
      "simpleDefinition": "Automatic Disconnection of Supply; a safety strategy that cuts power instantly when a fault occurs to prevent electric shock.",
      "anchor": "The system's 'auto-kill' switch for faults.",
      "misconception": "Thinking ADS is a single component; it is actually a system of parts working together."
    },
    {
      "term": "TN-S System",
      "simpleDefinition": "An earthing arrangement where the neutral and earth conductors are separate throughout the entire system back to the transformer.",
      "anchor": "S stands for Separate.",
      "misconception": "Confusing it with TN-C-S where the conductors are combined at the intake."
    },
    {
      "term": "TN-C-S System",
      "simpleDefinition": "An earthing arrangement where the neutral and earth are combined into one conductor for part of the supply, then separated at the consumer's intake.",
      "anchor": "C stands for Combined.",
      "misconception": "Believing the earth and neutral remain combined inside the building's final circuits."
    },
    {
      "term": "TT System",
      "simpleDefinition": "An earthing arrangement where the installation is connected to earth via a local electrode (rod) rather than a supplier's cable.",
      "anchor": "Terra-Terra (Earth to Earth).",
      "misconception": "Assuming the supplier always provides the earth connection."
    },
    {
      "term": "Circuit Protective Conductor (CPC)",
      "simpleDefinition": "The specific wire that connects the metal parts of an individual circuit to the main earthing terminal.",
      "anchor": "The green and yellow wire in a standard cable.",
      "misconception": "Calling this the 'earthing conductor'; the CPC is only for the individual circuit."
    },
    {
      "term": "Earthing Conductor",
      "simpleDefinition": "The main conductor that connects the installation's Main Earthing Terminal to the actual means of earthing (like the supplier's cable or an electrode).",
      "anchor": "The 'bridge' between the house and the earth source.",
      "misconception": "Using this term to describe the smaller CPC wires inside a circuit."
    },
    {
      "term": "Main Protective Bonding",
      "simpleDefinition": "Conductors used to connect metal services (like gas or water pipes) to the main earthing terminal to keep them at the same voltage.",
      "anchor": "Safety connection for incoming metal pipes.",
      "misconception": "Thinking bonding is meant to carry fault current like a CPC; its job is to equalize voltage."
    },
    {
      "term": "Supplementary Bonding",
      "simpleDefinition": "Additional bonding used in high-risk areas, such as bathrooms, to connect all touchable metal parts together.",
      "anchor": "Extra safety connections for wet zones.",
      "misconception": "Thinking every room in a house requires supplementary bonding."
    },
    {
      "term": "Protective Device",
      "simpleDefinition": "A component like a fuse or circuit breaker that automatically breaks the circuit during an overcurrent or fault.",
      "anchor": "The 'trip switch' or fuse.",
      "misconception": "Believing a protective device only protects against fire; it is a critical part of shock protection (ADS)."
    },
    {
      "term": "Earth Electrode",
      "simpleDefinition": "A metal rod, plate, or mesh driven into the ground to provide a physical connection to the earth.",
      "anchor": "The 'earth rod' in the garden.",
      "misconception": "Thinking every house has one; they are primarily used in TT systems."
    }
  ],
  "anchorPhrases": [
    "Separate earth path back to the source",
    "Combined neutral and earth supply",
    "Local connection to the ground",
    "Automatic Disconnection of Supply",
    "Circuit-specific protection"
  ],
  "misconceptionTargets": [
    "The difference between the Earthing Conductor and the CPC",
    "The difference between Earthing and Bonding",
    "When an Earth Electrode is actually required",
    "The specific meaning of S (Separate) and C (Combined) in TN systems"
  ]
}

[
  {
    "title": "Earthing System Types",
    "objective": "Identify and distinguish between TT, TN-S, and TN-C-S earthing arrangements.",
    "retrievalTextLines": [
      "In the UK, we use three main earthing arrangements to ensure fault current has a safe path back to the transformer. The names tell you exactly how the earth and neutral conductors are handled. In a TN-S system, the 'S' stands for Separate. This means the neutral and earth conductors are separate all the way from the source to the installation. The supplier usually provides an earth connection via the metal sheath of their cable.",
      "In a TN-C-S system, the 'C' stands for Combined. Here, the supplier combines the neutral and earth into a single conductor for the street mains, but they are separated into two distinct terminals at your intake position. This is the most frequent setup you will encounter in modern domestic properties.",
      "Finally, there is the TT system, or 'Terra-Terra'. In this arrangement, the supplier provides no earth terminal at all. Instead, the installer must provide a local connection to the ground by driving an earth electrode, such as a copper-clad steel rod, into the soil to create a return path."
    ],
    "hint": "Focus on what the letters S and C stand for, and remember that TT requires the installer to provide their own connection to the ground."
  },
  {
    "title": "ADS Component Parts",
    "objective": "Identify the six core components that facilitate Automatic Disconnection of Supply.",
    "retrievalTextLines": [
      "Automatic Disconnection of Supply (ADS) is the primary safety strategy used to prevent electric shock. It is not a single component, but a chain of parts working together to cut power during a fault. The earthing conductor is the main cable connecting the installation's main earthing terminal to the earth source. From there, every individual circuit uses a Circuit Protective Conductor (CPC) to link the metal casing of equipment back to the consumer unit.",
      "To keep everything at the same voltage and prevent shocks from metalwork, we use main protective bonding to connect incoming metal gas and water pipes to the earth terminal. In high-risk areas like bathrooms, we may also use supplementary bonding to link all touchable metal parts together. The 'muscle' of the system is the protective device, such as a fuse or circuit breaker, which trips to cut the power. In TT systems, an earth electrode is also required to provide the physical connection to the ground. Missing any one of these parts can break the safety chain and leave the installation dangerous."
    ],
    "hint": "Distinguish between the earthing conductor (the main link) and the CPC (the circuit-specific wire), and remember that bonding is for metal pipes and wet zones."
  }
]

